AGI - The White House was the scene of a rather hard confrontation between Elon Musk and Marco Rubio, which would end with Donald Trump's decision to leave the individual ministries the decision on the budget cuts that had been demanded to the DOGE led by the patron of Tesla. The New York Times reports it, which gives a long report of a lively cabinet meeting citing five sources, but denied by the President of the United States.&nbsp;
According to the New York Times, last Thursday, Musk fought first with Rubio and, separately, with the Secretary of Transport Sean Duffy. The cuts decided by Musk led to tensions in Trump's cabinet that, after the meeting, announced that the cuts would continue but with a "waste" rather than with an "ax", implying that he took the opportunity to hold Musk. "No clash. I was there, too," said the president, continuing to insist that Musk and Rubio "they both do a fantastic job, they both agree fantastically." &nbsp;
According to the NYT article, Musk would have billed Rubio's cost cuts to the State Department, accusing him of not firing "no" in the first 45 days of the administration. Rubio replied that 1,500 officials of the State Department had accepted early retirement and asked sarcasically if he should only summarize them to fire them again more spectacularly. Musk responded by telling Rubio that he was "good on TV," with the clear sense that he was not good at doing much more. During the exchange, the president sat down, conserted arms, as if he was watching a tennis game. After the discussion dragged on for an awkward moment, he intervened to say that Rubio is doing a "good job", he has a lot to think about, he is always on the road and has an agency to manage. So he invited everyone to work together.
The meeting was a potential turning point and it is the first significant indication that Trump is willing to put limits to Musk, whose initiatives have become the subject of several lawsuits and have aroused concerns from Republican parliamentarians, some of whom complained directly with the president. In another harsh exchange of jokes, Duffy accused DOGE of trying to fire vital air traffic controllers just as the country is facing the consequences of several air accidents, and Musk would accuse him of being a liar. Trump would finally intervene to stop the discussion and suggest that from now on flight controllers are hired among the "genies" studying at the prestigious Massachusetts Institute&nbsp;of&nbsp;Technology.&nbsp;
Most cabinet members didn't join the mix. Musk's anger, especially addressed to Rubio, seemed to have caught surprise the present and caustic answers of the DOGE boss may have discouraged other cabinet members, many of whom complained privately about Musk's team, from talking. Since he entered office, Trump's administration has fired or announced the departure of tens of thousands of federal employees in a burnt ground efficiency campaign. Several U.S. media reported frictions between Musk and senior officials, accusing his young team of DOGE officials, recruited in the Silicon Valley, to have abused his authority. It is unclear what will be the long-term impact of the meeting. Musk remains the president's biggest financial supporter: just this week it sent advertising for a value of 1 million dollars that said "Thank you, President Trump".<br> &nbsp;

